  ('medicine-ball-lateral-shuffle-pass', 'The ball gives immediate feedback: speed, accuracy, rebound, catch quality, or load path changes when the athlete leaks force. Medicine Ball Lateral Shuffle Pass therefore links bracing, timing, and force transfer in a coachable way.', 'Belongs in Movement Intelligence because the primary adaptation is timing, coordination, perception-action quality, spatial awareness, or clean movement selection before fatigue corrupts learning.', 'Use after warm-up and before fatigue-heavy work while the athlete can learn, read cues, adjust feet, catch, and reset without conditioning drift.', 'The common mistake is adding chaos, speed, partner pressure, or ball speed before the athlete can read the cue, catch/throw accurately, brake, and reset.', 'Scale by reducing cue choices, object speed, partner distance, locomotion speed, or turn angle before adding unpredictability. Progress only one variable at a time and let the quality gate decide.'),
